`buttons` only exists inside of Home -- you can&#39;t reference it from a Shop instance. Any logic to interact with the `buttons` array needs to be exposed via methods.

The code you provided shouldn&#39;t even compile because `buttons` is &quot;invisible&quot; to shop. 

---

In a comment you said:

&gt; If I switch to the shop page, a panel overlays the frame from the home class so the buttons need to get deactivated. If I go back, I have to reactivate the buttons.

You&#39;d want to do something like this:

```
class Home {

    JButton[] buttons = new JButton[4];

    public void setButtonActiveState(boolean isActive) {
        for (JButton button : buttons) {
            button.setEnabled(isActive);
        }
    }

    // this is whatever your &#39;setup&#39; method is that is adding all of the listeners
    public void setup() {
        // notice, passing a reference to Home to shop.
        Shop shop = new Shop(this);

        buttons[2].addActionListener(new ActionListener() { 
            @Override
            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
                shop.setVisible(true);

                setButtonActiveState(false);
            }
        });
    }
}

class Shop {

    // a reference to home
    private final Home home;
    public Shop(Home home) {
        this.home = home;
    }

    // call this method when you close Shop
    void onClose() {

        // reactivate the home buttons
        this.home.setButtonActiveState(true);

    }
}
```

Basically, Shop needs to know about Home -- but it must not create a _new_ Home ... there&#39;s already a Home instance so we should just reuse that. I did this by passing the Home instance to Shop in the constructor.

when Shop is closed, invoke the `onClose` method, which will then set the active state of the buttons in Home. Since the structure of Shop is a mystery, you&#39;ll need to apply that to the button or other closing mechanism (eg. keypress) yourself.

I also renamed your methods and variables: in Java you should use camelCase, not snake_case. Further you only need one method to toggle between button states, not two, since the only difference is a boolean variable.

